<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-353-610  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 353 610.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  April 16 1990 n296 pS3(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Into the future--gradually. (prospects for the implementation offiber optics) (Special Report: the technology of tomorrow)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schultz, Beth.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Fiber optics is generally regarded as the key to theimplementation of integrated services digital network (ISDN)features and the transport medium that will dominate the publicnetwork of the future.andP;  At the same time, Bell regional holdingcompanies and other communications service suppliers are currentlycontending with the economics of fiber optic installation.andP;  Thisrequires balancing the bottom line needs of the telephonecompanies against the need of customers for the advanced servicesthat ISDN, with its extensive bandwidth capacity, makes possible.andO;Since Illinois Bell first deployed fiber in a 1.5-mile link in1977, the deployment of fiber has increased to a 1989 figure of1.24 million miles.andP;  Analysts predict that by 1993, there will bemore than 1.86 million miles of installed fiber in the US.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber OpticsBell Regional Holding CompaniesTelephone SystemsStrategic PlanningCost Benefit AnalysisCommunications TechnologyOutlook.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>